API response. The step name should match since it comes directly from `s.name` in the workflow steps. I keep going in circles here, so maybe I should just write a test to see what actually happens when this handler runs. Actually, wait—I should check something simpler first: whether the `Content-Type: text/plain` header is being set before or after the response is written.\n\nLooking at the flow again, I think I found it. The `Content-Type` header gets set on line 1175, then if the file read fails, `http.Error` is called on line 1200, which tries to set the header again. Once headers are written, subsequent `Set` calls don't take effect, so there might be a conflict there.\n\nActually, wait — the real issue is probably in how the file path is being extracted. Let me check that function again to see if it's stripping the path correctly. So the actual length is 36, and val[6:34] extracts positions 6 through 33, which gives me `.cloche/prompts/implement.` — but that's missing the final `md` part, so I need to adjust the slice to val[6:35] to get the complete filename.\n\nNow let me look at the JavaScript code that constructs the drawer HTML to see if the real issue is in how the step data is being rendered there. I'm realizing the HTML structure looks correct with the drawer-content div positioned after the definition list. But I should actually run this and see what happens, or reconsider the approach entirely. Let me check the handler registration for the step content endpoint again to make sure the routing is set up properly.\n\nNow I'm tracing through the fetch URL construction to verify it matches the Go route pattern—the project, workflow, and step names should map correctly to the path parameters. The URL encoding shouldn't be an issue for typical names like \"develop\" or \"implement,\" though I'm wondering if there could be edge cases with special characters in workflow or step names.\n\nActually, I'm starting to suspect the real problem might be that a differ