0,0,0,0.1);\n    transition: right 0.25s ease;\n    z-index: 100;\n    display: flex;\n    flex-direction: column;\n    overflow: hidden;\n}\n\n.drawer.drawer-open { right: 0; }\n\n.drawer-header {\n    display: flex;\n    justify-content: space-between;\n    align-items: center;\n    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;\n    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);\n    font-weight: 700;\n    font-size: 1rem;\n}\n\n.drawer-close {\n    background: none;\n    border: none;\n    font-size: 1.4rem;\n    cursor: pointer;\n    color: var(--text-muted);\n    padding: 0 0.25rem;\n}\n\n.drawer-close:hover { color: var(--text); }\n\n.drawer-body {\n    padding: 1rem;\n    overflow-y: auto;\n    flex: 1;\n}\n\n.drawer-body pre {\n    background: var(--bg);\n    border: 1px solid var(--border);","numLines":50,"startLine":490,"totalLines":577}}}
[2026-03-09T15:31:25Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01NdRVUCpgFUb2ZkRuGFztX2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CSS looks fine. The drawer-body has overflow-y: auto and flex: 1, so it should show scrollable content.\n\nLet me think about this from another angle. Let me look at the handler one more time and trace through the actual data flow:\n\n1. API returns workflow data including step config\n2. Frontend clicks step node → calls openDrawer(workflowName, stepName)\n3. openDrawer shows step metadata including filename\n4. openDrawer fetches `/api/projects/.../workflows/.../steps/.../content`\n5. Handler reads the file and returns contents\n\nWait, could the issue be that the handler is matching the step content but the file path used by `resolveProjectDir` fails because the project directory doesn't match? Or maybe the issue is that this is a race condition - the template data hasn't fully loaded when someone clicks?\n \nLooking at the drawer template and how it gets populated - the drawer starts empty, and when openDrawer is called, it injects the content directly into the drawer-body element and adds the open class to display it.\n\nThe next thinking is examining what happens when the fetch request completes. The body string includes a loading placeholder div with id \"drawer-content\", so after the initial innerHTML assignment, that element exists in the DOM. The fetch then runs asynchronously, and when the response arrives, it tries to find and update that same drawer-content div.\n\nThe issue is that if the drawer gets closed and reopened between when it's first opened and when the fetch completes, the innerHTML gets replaced entirely, so the drawer-content div no longer exists. This would cause the fetch callback to fail silently when trying to update a non-existent element.\n\nBut the user is seeing the filename, which means the drawer is opening successfully. The problem might be that an error is being thrown somewhere in the fetch chain that's getting swallowed, or there's something else preventing the content from actually rendering once it arrives.\n\nLooking at the server response handling, I'm wondering if the issue is with how the file path is being resolved. The workflow config specifies the prompt file with a `.cloche/` prefix, but I need to check whether that path is being preserved correctly when the handler reads the file.\n\nLet me trace through the path construction: `extractFilePath` pulls `.cloche/prompts/implement.md`, then `filepath.Join` combines it with the project directory to create the full path. If the project directory is `/home/user/myproject`, the result should be `/home/user/myproject/.cloche/prompts/implement.md`, which looks right.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be in how `resolveProjectDir` matches the project label from the URL path against the actual project directories. The function creates a label map from directory names, but if the label matching isn't working correctly, it could be resolving to the wrong directory entirely.\n\nLet me check the DSL parser's `parseValue` function to see if it's handling the function call syntax correctly...\n\nWriting parser logic... Tracing through the token sequence, the string token gets wrapped in quotes and appended to the buffer, then the closing parenthesis is consumed, yielding the final reconstructed expression `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")`.\n\nI'm hitting a wall with static analysis, so let me actually test the endpoint to see what's happening. But wait—rereading the issue, it says the filename displays but the file contents don't load. What if the drawer is being populated correctly but just isn't visible? Maybe there's a CSS issue hiding the content, though the pre element styling looks fine.\n\nLet me trace through the drawer layout: the body has `flex: 1` to take remaining space in the flex column, which should work. The fetch URL should be correct too—Go 1.22 mux wildcards match anything except slashes, so hyphens in step names aren't a problem. Let me dig into what else could be preventing the content from showing.\n\nActually, I should check this from the browser side. Could there be a CORS issue? No, it's same-origin. A redirect? No redirect logic in the handler. Middleware blocking it? There's no middleware mentioned in the setup. Let me just write a test to see what's actually happening.\n\nNow looking at the fetch error handling more carefully—if there's a network error, the promise rejects and with no `.catch()` handler, the error gets silently swallowed while the drawer stays stuck on \"Loading content...\". But the issue says the filename is actually showing up, so the request must be succeeding somehow.\n\nActually, I think I found it—what if the problem is that `document.getElementById('drawer-content')` returns null? If the element doesn't exist when the response comes back, trying to set `innerHTML` would throw an error that gets silently swallowed since there's no error handler. And that could happen if someone clicks a different step while the first fetch is still in-flight, replacing the drawer content and destroying the element before the response arrives.\n\nLet me look at the template and handler code more carefully to trace through exactly what's happening. I'm reconsidering whether the fetch call is even executing in the deployed version, or if the response is genuinely empty. The handler code shows the fetch is there, but maybe the actual issue is that the file contents aren't being written properly on the backend, or the response is returning empty even though the files themselves have data.\n\nActually, I should check the template structure more carefully—specifically whether the scripts block that contains all the JavaScript is actually being included in the layout template at all.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_token